f=Engineering/dev/marketplace/git-workflow-and-versioning/SKILL.md · h2:Overview=Git your safety net. Treat commits save points, branches sandboxes, history documentation. agents generating code high speed, disciplined version control mechanism keeps changes manageable, reviewable, reversible. · wu=Always. code change flows through git. · h3:Trunk-Based Development (Recommended)=`main ──●──●──●──●──●──●──●──●──●──  (always deployable) \· ╲      ╱  ╲    ╱ \· ●──●─╱    ●──╱    ← short-lived feature branches (1-3 days)` · h3:Trunk-Based Development (Recommended)=Keep `main` always deployable. Work short-lived feature branches merge back within 1-3 days. Long-lived development branches hidden costs they diverge, create merge conflicts, delay integration. DORA research consistently shows trunk-based development correlates high-performing engineering teams. recommended default. Teams using gitflow long-lived branches adapt principles (atomic commits, small changes, descriptive messages) their branching model commit discipline matters specific branching strategy. · h3:Trunk-Based Development (Recommended)=**Dev branches costs.** day branch lives, accumulates merge risk., **Release branches acceptable.** you need stabilize release while main moves forward., **Feature flags long branches.** Prefer deploying incomplete work behind flags rather keeping branch weeks. · h3:Commit Early, Commit Often=`Work pattern: \· Implement slice → Test → Verify → Commit → Next slice \·  \· Not this: \· Implement everything → Hope it works → Giant commit` · h3:Commit Early, Commit Often=successful increment gets commit. Don't accumulate large uncommitted changes. Commits save points. next change breaks something, you revert last known-good state instantly. · h3:2. Atomic Commits=`# Good: Each commit is self-contained \· a1b2c3d Add task creation endpoint with validation \· d4e5f6g Add task creation form component \· h7i8j9k Connect form to API and add loading state \· m1n2o3p Add task creation tests (unit + integration)` · h3:2. Atomic Commits=commit one logical thing: · h3:3. Descriptive Messages=`<type>: <short description> \·  \· <optional body explaining why, not what>` · h3:3. Descriptive Messages=`# Good: Explains intent \· feat: add email validation to registration endpoint \·  \· Prevents invalid email formats from reaching the database. \· Uses schema validation at the route handler level,` · h3:3. Descriptive Messages=Commit messages explain *why*, *what*. **Format:** **Types:** `feat` (new feature) `fix` (bug fix) `refactor` (neither fixes adds) `test` (tests) `docs` (documentation) `chore` (tooling, dependencies, config) · h3:4. Keep Concerns Separate=`# Good: Separate concerns \· refactor: extract validation logic to shared utility \· feat: add phone number validation to registration \·  \· # Bad: Mixed concerns` · h3:4. Keep Concerns Separate=Don't combine formatting changes behavior changes. Don't combine refactors features. type change separate commit ideally separate PR: Small cleanups (renaming variable) included feature commit reviewer discretion. · h3:5. Size Your Changes=`~100 lines  → Easy to review, easy to revert \· ~300 lines  → Acceptable for a single logical change \· ~1000 lines → Split into smaller changes` · h3:5. Size Your Changes=Target ~100 lines commit/PR. Changes over ~1000 lines split (splitting strategies: see `code-review-standards`). · h2:Branching Strategy=`main (always deployable) \· ├── feature/task-creation    ← One feature per branch \· ├── feature/user-settings    ← Parallel work \· └── fix/duplicate-tasks      ← Bug fixes` · h2:Branching Strategy=Branch *policy* (which branches exist, protection rules, who merges) owned `delivery-governance` section supplies mechanics. · h2:Branching Strategy=Branch `main` (or team's default branch); merge within 1-3 days; delete after merge., Naming: `feature/<desc>` `fix/<desc>` `chore/<desc>` `refactor/<desc>`., Prefer feature flags over long-lived branches incomplete features. · h2:Working with Worktrees=`git worktree add ../project-feature-a feature/task-creation \· git worktree add ../project-feature-b feature/user-settings \· # ... each worktree is a separate directory with its own branch \· git worktree remove ../project-feature-a   # when done` · h2:Working with Worktrees=parallel agent work, use git worktrees run multiple branches simultaneously: Benefits: multiple agents work parallel without interfering; branch switching; failed experiment deleted worktree; changes stay isolated until explicitly merged. · h2:The Save Point Pattern=`Agent starts work \· ├── Makes a change \· │   ├── Test passes? → Commit → Continue \· │   └── Test fails?  → Revert to last commit → Investigate \· └── Feature complete → All commits form a clean history` · h2:The Save Point Pattern=You never lose one increment. agent goes off rails, `git reset --hard HEAD` returns last successful state. · h2:Change Summaries=`CHANGES MADE: \· - <file>: <what and why> \·  \· THINGS I DIDN'T TOUCH (intentionally): \· - <file>: <related gap, out of scope — separate task>` · h2:Change Summaries=After any modification, provide structured summary: "DIDN'T TOUCH" section especially important shows scope discipline, maps directly code-review-standards' over-broad-diff check. · h2:Pre-Commit Hygiene=Before commit: (1) review staged diff, (2) scan secrets (`password\|secret\|api_key\|token`), (3) run tests, (4) run linter, (5) run type checks. concrete commands (`npm test`, `eslint`, `tsc --noEmit`, hook tooling like husky/lint-staged) **stack examples bind real ones `stack-profile`**. Automate git hooks stack supports it. · h2:Handling Generated Files=**Commit generated files** project expects them (lockfiles, committed migrations)., **Don't commit** build output, environment files (`.env*`), personal IDE config., **Have `.gitignore`** covering dependencies, build dirs, env files, keys day one. · h2:Using Git for Debugging=`git bisect start && git bisect bad HEAD && git bisect good <known-good>   # find the breaking commit \· git log --oneline -20 \· git diff HEAD~5..HEAD -- <path>                   # what changed recently \· git blame <file>                                                          # who last changed a line \· git log --grep="<keyword>" --oneline                                      # search messages` · h2:Release & Versioning=Commits *you* track change; **version** your *consumers* track it. Once anything depends your code, version number changelog contract answering "what running, safe upgrade?" · h3:Semantic Versioning=`MAJOR.MINOR.PATCH`: **MAJOR** breaking (consumers change code) **MINOR** new, backward-compatible **PATCH** fix, backward-compatible. number promise. "patch" changes behavior consumers relied major disguise (Hyrum's Law see raj's `api-standards`). unsure whether change breaking, assume is. · h3:Tag release; tag source truth=`git tag -a v1.4.0 -m "Release 1.4.0" && git push origin v1.4.0` · h3:Tag release; tag source truth=Derive version tag rather hand-editing scattered files, artifact, tag, changelog never disagree. · h3:Keep changelog written humans=changelog `git log`. Group `Added Changed Fixed Deprecated Removed Security`, newest top, phrased user impact. Write entry **in change makes change** reconstructed release time. Breaking changes get migration note deprecation window (data-shape migrations: dana's `migration-discipline`); shipping release ops's `release-discipline` section versioning contract feeds it. · h2:Common Rationalizations=\| Rationalization \| Reality \| · h2:Common Rationalizations=\|---\|---\| · h2:Common Rationalizations=\| "I'll commit when the feature is done" \| One giant commit is impossible to review, debug, or revert. Commit each slice. \| · h2:Common Rationalizations=\| "The message doesn't matter" \| Messages are documentation for future agents and humans. \| · h2:Common Rationalizations=\| "I'll squash it all later" \| Squashing destroys the development narrative. \| · h2:Common Rationalizations=\| "Branches add overhead" \| Short-lived branches are free; long-lived ones are the problem. \| · h2:Common Rationalizations=\| "I'll split this change later" \| Split before submitting, not after. \| · h2:Common Rationalizations=\| "I don't need a .gitignore" \| Until `.env` with production secrets gets committed. \| · h2:Common Rationalizations=\| "It's just a small fix, bump the patch" \| Check what consumers can observe. Behavior change = major, whatever the diff size. \| · h2:Common Rationalizations=\| "The changelog is just the commit log" \| Commits are for you; the changelog is curated for consumers. \| · h2:Common Rationalizations=\| "We'll write the changelog at release time" \| By then half the impact is forgotten. Write it with the change. \| · h2:Red Flags=Large uncommitted changes messages like "fix"/"update"/"misc" formatting mixed behavior `.gitignore` committed secrets/build artifacts long-lived divergent branches force-pushing shared branches breaking change under minor/patch bump untagged release hand-edited version drift changelog that's dumped commit messages. · h2:Verification=commit: one logical thing message explains why, follows types tests pass first secrets diff mixed formatting/behavior `.gitignore` covers exclusions. release: bump matches change tagged, version derived tag curated changelog entry grouped impact. · b:with other skills=**delivery-governance (dev):** owns branch *policy*, DoD, Rail execution-plan artifact; skill supplies commit/branch/release *mechanics*. Conflict delivery-governance wins., **code-review-standards (dev):** consumes atomic commits change summaries; over-broad diffs flagged trace back violations here., **stack-profile (dev):** binds tooling examples (test/lint/typecheck commands, hook tooling) business., **api-standards (raj):** breaking-change judgment API surfaces (Hyrum's Law) lives there., **migration-discipline (dana):** versioned data-shape changes reversibility (Rail live there., **release-discipline (ops):** consumes tag changelog contract; owns deploy/rollback., **Security Charter:** senior skill; commits/pushes agents follow Rails 1–2 (plan-locked, sandboxed).